text.tspan: Figure t. Wickelfeature dictionary. We evaluated the performance of the network by comparing
the network's output to the Wickelfeature representation of the correct word. We see that all words
in the training set have high similarity (blue line), but also that the similarity increases beyond the
normal level. We also see that as more verb pairs are encountered that words in the test set also
increase in similarity to the correct answer in the feature space.
Figure u. Wickelfeature dictionary with regularization. We evaluate the network's performance by
comparing the output to the correct answer and measuring the similarity in the feature space. We
see that words in the training set start with high similarity and remain high (blue), indicating
one-shot learning. Words in the test set increase as more words are added in the training set and
common transformations are found and applied.
Figure v. Regularized dictionary cycle 2. We see that another cycle of the learning algorithm
through the training set begins to decrease the similarity, but this is because it was
over-emphasized at the end of the first cycle. The error of the training set decreases after the
second cycle. The test set performance slightly drops through the second cycle, but stays around
the same level. The test set error is slightly lower, but it is hard to tell if this improved
generalization performance.
Figure w. Wicklefeature dictionary on dataset (X) of max 20 principle components and without
singular values. We can see that dimensionality of N=1000 can be drastically reduced to N=20
with equivalent similarity behavior despite less smooth results.
Figure x. Wicklefeature least squares solution. The algorithm calculates the closed form
least squares solution to present tense verbs (X), and corresponding past tense verbs (Y) for a set
training set size. We can see perfect similarity with the training set up until 1000 words, equivalent
to N=1000. Its lower test similarities imply that the algorithm doesn't completely regularize or is
biased towards higher similarities by having the solution update via addition.
Figure y. Wickelfeature difference dictionary. The algorithm that stores the transform immediately
has some similarity with words in the test set, because the present-tense word is usually similar to
the past-tense word without any transformation. We again see the over-emphasis of certain
transformation features, leading to similarities going above N, where N=1000.
Figure z. Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization. We use the difference
algorithm with regularization and see that words in the training set have high similarity
throughout. Words in the test set start off with some similarity and increase. N=1000.
Figure a1. Second cycle of Wickelfeature difference dictionary with regularization.
We again see some improvement in the variance of the training set, but it is hard to tell
if there is improvement with test set generalization. N=1000.
